ublishers, editors, and peer reviewers**—to uphold the ethical and intellectual standards of scholarly work. This includes ensuring that AI tools are used responsibly, that AI-generated content is accurate, original, and free from plagiarism, and that the final published work does not mislead readers. Additionally, these stakeholders are tasked with maintaining the accuracy, validity, and integrity of research throughout the publication process, from creation to evaluation. Accountability in this context emphasizes the collective duty to preserve trust in academic discourse, particularly as the integration of AI into research and publishing practices continues to evolve.\",9\r\n64,DATA PRIVACY,\"The concept of \"\"DATA PRIVACY\"\" in the context of academic publishing and AI tools refers to the measures taken to protect personal, sensitive, and confidential data throughout the research and publication process. This includes ensuring compliance with relevant data protection laws and regulations when AI technologies are utilized in review, editorial, or research activities. The focus is on safeguarding data from unauthorized access, misuse, or breaches, with particular attention to the ethical and legal responsibilities of authors, publishers, and AI developers. Data privacy in this domain emphasizes the importance of maintaining confidentiality and integrity, especially when handling personal information that may be involved in academic workflows.\",6\r\n61,POLICY,\"The POLICY framework encompasses a range of guidelines and regulations established by various key stakeholders in academic publishing, including major publishers such as BMJ, Elsevier, Wiley, Emerald, Springer Nature, and Johns Hopkins University Press, as well as organizations like ISPOR, MIT Press, IEEE, and others. These policies address the ethical use of artificial intelligence (AI) and generative AI technologies, including large language models (LLMs), in the context of content submission, publicati